r be collectively devoted to any single ideal. Gaus defends the moral constitution of this pluralistic, open society, where the very clash and disagreement of ideals spurs all to better understand what their personal ideals of justice happen to be.Presenting an original framework for how we should think about morality, The Tyranny of the Ideal rigorously analyzes a theory of ideal justice more suitable for contemporary times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJustice. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066753008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400881048zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400881048.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016b2016  a978-3-11-066753-0  PUP eBook-Package 2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA21UPPPUP  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN